Not all people with diabetes are alike (your textbook isn‚Äôt accurate) Have you experienced this before? (It‚Äôs a HUGE pet peeve of mine). When people just ASSUME there is ONE way to handle living with diabetes. ‚ùåIt can be diet (keto only or only plant based or 45-60g carbs per meal) ‚ùå It can be exercise (only endurance sports are ok with blood sugars) ‚ùåIt can be insulin method (only pump vs only MDI) ‚ùå It can be limited reference experience (my son‚Äôs friend has T1D and he only eats fruit for dessert so here‚Äôs a melon) Not every Type 1 is the same as the rest. Sure, there are basic general principles that we ALL do (i.e. take medication) But not everyone should be managed the same way. üü¢What works for you may not work for me. üü¢What works for me may not work for someone else. üü¢What works for Karen‚Ä¶well, nothing works for Karen, just ask her. The most important thing is finding what method works best FOR YOU¬† Try different things (be smart, of course), see what fits, and make changes as needed. That is it. Have you found the method that works best for you to control your blood sugars? If not, no biggie, but don‚Äôt stop trying til you do üéâ #diabeteslife #diabetesawareness #insulindependent #bloodsugarmanagement #t1diabetes #diabetic #type1diabetes

Understanding life insurance: PART ONE: WHOLE LIFE INSURANCE. Whole life is permanent coverage, meaning as long as you are paying the premium the coverage will not go away. It also comes with the benefit of price lock and coverage lock which makes sure as you get older, your premium will not increase as well as your coverage amount will not decrease. Whole life insurance comes with a built-in cash value benefit, which is like having a savings account attached to the policy in which you can withdraw if needed without any penalty. most traditional whole life policies this isn‚Äôt going to be anything life changing however will make sure to start covering your final expenses. Whole life insurance is most likely the type of insurance you have heard from your grandparents or possibly someone from an older generation; Most of the time whole life insurance are usually for people who are 40 and over, however now can be offered to people who are younger. The coverage amounts of whole life insurance are smaller amounts of $50,000 or less and for the most part it is intended for burial purposes and final expenses. It‚Äôs to make sure we don‚Äôt end up leaving a bill or being a financial burden for those we love who are simply still living when we die. #wholelifeinsurance #wholelife #wholelifepolicy #wholelifeinsurancepolicy #termlifeinsurance #termlifeinsurancepolicy #iul #IUL #fyp„Ç∑„Çöviral #FYP #family #singlemoms #singledads #baby #married #son #daughter #father #mother #mortgage #finalexpenseinsurance #finalexpense #insurancebroker #retirementplanning #retirementincome #taxfreeretirement #legacybuilding #financialliteracy #financiallearning #generationalwealth #legacybuilding  #ibc #infinitebankingconcept #generationalwealth #connecticut #hartfordct #middletownct #middletownny #pennsylvania #ohio #stamfordct #glastonburyct #bushnellparkhartford #northcarolina #charlottenc #albanyny #romeny #heartattack #cancer #stroke #tia #diabeties #kidneyfailure #kidneydisease #asthma #vet #veteran #army #navy #marines #airforce #nationalguard #animals #computerscience #computers

3 more things that will impact your blood sugars that are NOT food or activity related. When you get diabetes, you are always told how carbs and exercise will make your blood sugar bounce all over the place.¬† But there‚Äôs actually a ton of other things that may impact tem as well. Here‚Äôs 3 more: 1. Allergies -¬† Allergies ‚û°Ô∏è inflammation inflammation ‚û°Ô∏è cortisol cortisol ‚û°Ô∏è an unfriendly beast that can wreak havoc on raising your blood sugars.¬† Definitely will want to talk with your care team about some seasonal allergy remedy to make sure that you're not impacted nearly as dramatically, especially as allergy season is starting to bloom. 2. Corticosteroids - Sometimes your doctor may want to give you a cortisone injection or a round of oral steroids for an illness that you have and that can single-handedly just destroy your blood sugar.¬† I‚Äôm talking blood sugars in the high 300s-400s for potentially days if you‚Äôre not careful.¬†¬† Because it can destroy your insulin sensitivity, you have to make sure you have a strategy for that because you could change nothing else and still have absolutely insane blood sugars. 3. Stress - Stress will single-handedly wreck your blood sugar through a similar mechanism to allergies, minus the actual allergen part. Cortisol can destroy your blood sugar so mental health is absolutely huge to pay attention to. 3 healthier low BG snack options to consider from a RD/CDE who lives with T1D¬†¬† First of all, during a low blood sugar episode, ‚Äúhealthy‚Äù should not be the top priority. The top priority is getting your blood sugar back into range in the safest way possible (and to keep it in range). However, if you‚Äôre looking for something with a few extra nutritional benefits, I‚Äôve got 3 for you right here: 1. Raisins or other dry fruit.¬† Because it‚Äôs dried fruit, it tends to be absorbed a lot faster and tends to be a high concentrate of glucose.¬† In something like raisins, there tends to be a bunch of potassium, some B-vitamins, a teeny bit of fiber, and they are super portable. 2. Juice - everyone‚Äôs favorite classic.¬† Could be orange juice or apple juice, completely up to you. Because it's a liquid form it's going to be absorbed a lot faster.¬† You‚Äôve also got potassium here and it contributes toward your hydration, which is never a bad thing especially when it's warm outside. It‚Äôs also fairly portable. 3. Fairlife chocolate milk.¬† Of course, this would have to be stored in a fridge, so it may be a good option for when you are at home. It got 13g of carbs in one cup, which is fantastic, but it also had protein and a little bit of fat to help stabilize your blood sugar in addition to a ton of minerals, vitamins, and even some potassium. ‚Ä®What‚Äôs your go to low snack? #lowbloodsugar #typeonediabetes #diabeteslife #t1diabetes #diabeteseducator #hypoglycemia #type1diabetic #diabetesawareness #diabetessnacks #diabetestype1

Giving random insulin doses for food is like playing Russian roulette‚Ä¶literally. So why do you do it?¬† I hear this one FAR too often: ‚ÄúI have no idea what is in that food, so I'm just going to take X units and hope for the best.‚Äù What makes you think this is a good idea? There‚Äôs three possible outcomes: ü•ïYou NAIL the dose (highly unlikely) ü•ïYou underestimate and end up with a really high blood sugar (highly likely) ü•ïYou overestimate and end up with a really low blood sugar (also highly likely). It‚Äôs dangerous, and there‚Äôs so many resources out there that can help you have a better idea of what to dose‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶because let‚Äôs be real: you may not know EXACTLY. But, it‚Äôs better to use the information at your disposal to make a more educated dose than just an arbitrary number‚Ä¶ #type1diabetes #diabetesproblems #insulindependent #highbloodsugar #diabeteseducator #diabetesdiet #bloodsugarmanagement #diabetesmellitus #t1dlookslikeme #typeonediabetic #diabeteslife #type1diabetic

How does blood sugar control impact thyroid health? Diabetes and thyroid health are very much connected. This is why those with type 1 and 2 diabetes will often experience symptoms related to low thyroid health or receive a diagnosis, like hypothyroidism or Hashimoto‚Äôs. Thyroid hormone is a hormone that supports the health of every single cell in the body, which is trillions of cells. If you think about it, that‚Äôs a lot of different areas and functions, including: üëâ Mental health, like anxiety, stress, and depression üëâ Physical health, like energy, digestion, sleep‚Ä®üëâ Lab work, like cholesterol, blood pressure, and blood sugar The link between diabetes and thyroid hormone can be explained with a car. Thyroid hormone is like a driver of the car, or make the car speed up or slow down. Metabolism is like the car itself, or the aspect that uses fuel so we can go from point A to point B. Carbs are the gas the car uses so it can keep on moving. Carbs are the gas because they are needed to make thyroid hormone useable. Most of the thyroid hormone produced is not in its usable form and has a ‚Äúplastic seal.‚Äù Just like a new supplement bottle, you can't get to the capsules until you remove the seal. You can‚Äôt get to the capsules until you remove the seal. Same thing is true for thyroid hormone. And guess what removes the ‚Äúplastic seal‚Äù on thyroid hormone? Carbs! Specifically carbs that are stored in the liver. And guess what population has the lowest stores of these carbs? People experiencing uncontrolled blood sugar! Have you ever heard about the connection between blood sugar and thyroid health? . . . #balancedbloodsugars #diabetes #thyroidhealth #diabetessupport #diabetescommunity #diabeteslife #diabetesawareness #diabetestype1 #registereddieitian

I‚Äôm sure if you‚Äôve had diabetes for more than 10 minutes, someone inevitably has mixed up your diabetes with another type of diabetes‚Ä¶. And there‚Äôs nothing worse than when Aunt Marcy tells you to drink some okra water or snort some cinnamon to improve your blood sugar. Put simply, you can think of diabetes like this: Type 1 diabetes: when your pancreas quits on the job. It refuses to show up, it quits working; that‚Äôs it. Type 2 diabetes: where your pancreas is working overtime and it can‚Äôt keep up with the demand of what the insulin requirements are for the body‚Ä¶. ‚Ä¶So it works so hard that it starts burning itself out and eventually can‚Äôt function anymore. Type 1 is autoimmune (something triggers it) and Type 2 happens over time. And while there can be genetic predisposition to T2D, that is not the only cause. They found that the subjects that didn‚Äôt eat breakfast, had worse blood sugar not just in the morning, but also throughout the rest of the day! Your circadian rhythm manages things like: sleep, insulin sensitivity, cholesterol levels and even weight loss. Here are the first few steps to consider if you have recently been diagnosed with gestational diabetes: For many of the clients that I‚Äôve worked with over the years, their first reaction is their mind going a million different directions.  My first recommendation is to simply take a deep breath. I understand the worry that is going to go through a lot of women‚Äôs heads when they hear this news. At the same time, if you put all of your focus on worrying it will not be supportive towards your blood sugars. Potentially causing more insulin resistance.  Find what brings you back to center, whether it‚Äôs: deep breathing, exercise or chatting with your partner should be your first move.  Second, I would look at your nourishment. Many women that enter gestational diabetes are normally malnourished. This means you are not getting all the nutrients that you need to thrive. The more you focus on this, the more supportive your blood sugars will be. Third, look at how much movement you are including into your daily life. If you can get outside and reset that circadian rhythm, the better blood sugar readings that you‚Äôll find.  Fourth, look at how you can monitor your blood sugar readings so you can adjust throughout the day. If you‚Äôre on an insulin pump and you haven‚Äôt seen this - you need to know what it is. I‚Äôve had an insulin pump for over 20 years #old You may notice that in the box where your infusion sets come from is this little plastic piece. You might be thinking, ‚Äúwhy is this in the box? What is the purpose of this? I never use it.‚Äù You are SUPPOSED to plug it into your site when you disconnect your pump, so the site is not left open. For example: when you shower, go to the beach, or swim the pool. This way, nothing can get into your site. Do you actually need to use this thing? I‚Äôm supposed to tell you yes - leaving your site open to the elements can lead to things potentially getting in there (i.e. bacteria, sand, etc), the site may not work as effectively, etc. However, in all reality, I haven‚Äôt personally used it in about 8 years. It‚Äôs a pain to remember where it is - it‚Äôs not easy to carry it around with you without losing it -¬† and it ultimately doesn't make a massive difference unless you are in a situation where you are outdoors and something like sand or mud can get into your site. In that case you‚Äôd probably want to change it anyway when you're done. But let me know - did you know this thing was there and do you choose to use it? As we were working together, she actually became pregnant, which is super exciting for her and her family! üéâ The interesting thing that happened during that time, is that her blood sugars seemingly overnight went into the 80s! Here are 5 ways that regular monitoring helps people with Type 2 Diabetes: #1: It helps to determine if you are meeting your glucose targets: 80-130 mg/dl fasting or before a meal and < 180 2 hours after eating. #2: It helps to reduce unpleasant symptoms of high + low blood sugar, such as sleepiness and sluggishness, and anxiety and agitation respectively. #3: It helps to avoid long-term diabetes complications, such as neuropathy (feet), retinopathy (eyes), nephropathy (kidneys), and amputations. #4: It helps to identify what makes your numbers go up or down, like specific foods, meals, activities, stressors, and the impact of medications or supplements. #5: It helps you learn what to do and when to improve the time you spend most of your time within the blood sugar target range. Honey moon phase in type 1 diabetes Explained: So, let's talk about the honeymoon phase in type 1 diabetes. In type 1 diabetes, the antibodies start attacking the pancreas. So, this results in high glucose. This high glucose also attacks the pancreas, thereby causing a worsening of insulin deficiency. So starting insulin treatment right away relieves the pancreas, allowing you to produce insulin for a while, although it still requires support. This is known as the honeymoon phase, where the pancreas is still partially functioning. So, the patients will still need insulin, but not necessarily in large doses, since the pancreas is providing some support. So, this honeymoon phase can last for months or even years. Maintaining proper blood sugar control is essential to prevent additional damage caused by high glucose levels. So, unfortunately, the honeymoon phase in type 1 diabetes will not last forever. Eventually, the antibodies continue to destroy the beta cells of the pancreas, and the patient starts needing more insulin as time goes by. It is also important to note that the honeymoon phase does not occur in all individuals with type 1 diabetes. Some people may rapidly decline insulin production without experiencing this temporary improvement in blood sugar control. #insulintreatment #diabetestips #diabetesmanagement #chronicillness #diabetesdiet #endocrinology #healthadvices #diabetesfacts #medical #diabetesawareness #endocrineglands #diabetescontrol #diabetesprevention #healthawareness #healthcare #diabetesresearch #insulintherapy #insulindependent #diabetescommunity #healtheducation #healthadvocacy #glucosecontrol #endocrinologist #healthandwellness #diabeteslife #patientcare #insulinresistance #type1diabetes #diabetescare #hormonehealth

Let‚Äôs say you‚Äôre on a long flight and you NEED to eat, but you're afraid of a high blood sugar from whatever nasty food they have at the airport or give to you on the plane. Your pro-tip? Bring your own food from home. Yes, there will be a certain amount of time before its not safe from a food safety perspective (if its refrigerated‚Ä¶. But, it will give you a ton of peace of mind knowing exactly what the carb counts are and exactly what you need to do to dose for‚Ä¶ As opposed to guessing on lord knows what overpriced food that tastes like cardboard from the airport. This is the reason why your blood sugar goes up at 3am for no reason at all.¬† (There‚Äôs actually a very good reason). Trust me, it is ROUGH when you: üõèÔ∏èwent to bed and had a great blood sugar¬† üõèÔ∏èyou wake up with a high blood sugars‚Ä¶ üõèÔ∏èyou look at your continuous glucose monitor and notice that around 3am your blood sugar went up about 60 points and stayed there So now you‚Äôre waking up, you're groggy, you're dehydrated with a dry mouth, and your day is off to a less than great start. But here‚Äôs what is happening‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶your body is recovering from the previous day by releasing growth hormones and other hormones called catecholamines.¬†¬† In its repairing state, your body says to the liver to ‚Äúdump some glucose bro!‚Äù¬† ‚Ä¶and as a result, your blood sugar rises. So what can you do about this? This comes down specifically to a medication tweak.¬† If you are on an insulin pump, typically this can be achieved by changing your basal rate with your care team. If you aren‚Äôt on a pump, it can be a little more complicated, but there are ways to adjust it with your bolus rate or a correction dose (with your care team‚Äôs guidance). If you are on a different type of medication for Type 2, definitely discuss with your care team for timing of your meds to break through this.¬† This is a major thing that can and will affect your overnight blood sugars and remember, overnight blood sugars are over ‚Öì (!!) of your A1c. If this has happened and hasn‚Äôt been addressed yet, it's time. Whether that‚Äôs making healthy meals, exercising, or checking their blood sugar, or using their insulin pump or CGM it starts with you! #2: Help them do it. Whether that is helping them prepare a snack or a meal, giving them an idea, or working on it together so they‚Äôre able to learn the process and get in the habit of doing it daily. #3: Have them do it on their own. After you‚Äôve modeled the good habit and have done it alongside them, consider loosening the reins and encourage them to try it out on their own, make mistakes, and learn. Blood sugar rising for no reason when you wake up? (read this) An age old mystery up there with the Rosetta Stone and Where in the World is Carmen San Diego? This used to happen to me EVERY. SINGLE. DAY.¬† For years. It wasn‚Äôt until I was in grad school that I figured out the reason behind this. You wake up, go about your business, your blood sugar starts rising, you haven‚Äôt eaten or had anything to drink, but it keeps going up and up‚Ä¶¬† Suddenly you‚Äôre 225. Why is this happening?¬† Your liver is dumping glucose because it thinks you need energy. And while that‚Äôs really considerate of your liver, this ain‚Äôt the time or place. So, you may need to address that with a dose (and make sure you run that by your care team first and make sure you are doing what‚Äôs appropriate for you). Yes, it‚Äôs annoying but a minor inconvenience. Having great blood sugars or ignoring the obvious and feeling like garbage? I‚Äôll let you decide. Keep track of the fat and protein.¬†¬† While they aren‚Äôt going to hit you right now‚Ä¶if you‚Äôre having your get-together at 3-4PM, the fat and protein may come back to haunt you at 7-8PM‚Ä¶. which can be absolutely nightmarish. I couldn‚Äôt eat Swiss breakfast because of my diabetes‚Ä¶ Well I totally could have but it would have been a terrible life decision. You see in Switzerland, breakfast normally consists of some sort of baked good (i.e. croissant), some juice, and some fruit. ‚Ä®So, examining the nutritional breakdown as the nutrition nerd that I am, we‚Äôre looking at fast-acting carb + fast-acting carb + fast-acting carb + fat.¬† Combining that with being more insulin resistant in the morning, that breakfast was a first-class one-way ticket to a high blood sugar for no reason and was not going to help me get closer to my nutritional goals and targets for the day. So, we made our own breakfast. Fortunately our room had a kitchen. In a situation where you have a meal that‚Äôs offered that‚Äôs just straight carbs, try to have a backup plan where you can introduce protein, fiber, and some sort of quality fat source so that your blood sugars can stay happy, you can feel your best, and you can enjoy! #swissbreakfast #typeonediabetes #diabeteslife #diabetesdiet #insulindependent #bloodsugarbalance #highbloodsugar

There‚Äôs normally SOMETHING that causes that blood sugar to be out of range. The key? Figuring out what that thing is, eliminating it, and making sure you don‚Äôt repeat it in the future. #diabetesproblems #typeonediabetes #diabeteslife #diabetesawareness #insulindependent #t1diabetes #bloodsugar

This is what living with diabetes is like. Picture this:‚Ä® You‚Äôre about to do a crazy awesome hike‚Ä¶. But the hike is an hour away. You‚Äôre going to be gone for 5-6 hours, so you‚Äôre only going to have one opportunity to eat a real meal ahead of time. But you know you‚Äôre going to be sitting for an hour in transit, so you don‚Äôt want your blood sugar to spike super high while you're sitting on the way to the hike‚Ä¶ ‚Ä®But you also don‚Äôt want too much active insulin on board when you actually START the hike because otherwise your blood sugar will crash.¬† Then, once you're at the hike, even if your blood sugar is perfect, you still need to make sure it stays in range while you're hiking so you don‚Äôt have to stop the entire group and slow everyone down. So you‚Äôre not just thinking about the meal your going to eat before the hike‚Ä¶ and the type of food your going to eat before the hike to fuel yourself‚Ä¶ but you're thinking about: - the transit time -the actual hike itself -not tanking DURING the hike -not tanking OVERNIGHT AFTER the hike So you‚Äôre thinking two minutes, twenty minutes, and twenty hours into the future with diabetes. If you don‚Äôt have diabetes, you may not understand that that is the case. #diabetesproblems #diabeteslife #insulindependent #bloodsugarmanagement #typeonediabetes #diabetesawareness #diabetic #diabetesmanagement

2 steps to acclimate your diabetes faster to a new time zone. Recently, I took an international trip with Amelia and we were 6 hours ahead of our normal time zone. So, here‚Äôs the 2 steps I took to adjust my body and my blood sugars to our new location faster:‚Ä®‚Ä®1. Took out my insulin pump 2. Changed the time to local time That‚Äôs it. Why did I do this?‚Ä®‚Ä®Because it helps my body to acclimate to the current time. Otherwise, my body is operating 6 hours behind (on US time) and therefore, my settings are going to be off. So if I went to eat a meal, I may be getting more or less insulin than expected, as both basal and bolus needs may be different, and that can lead to a blood sugar nightmare. If you‚Äôre on injections, it‚Äôs a little different: you‚Äôll have to change your basal rate timing to keep things steady. Did your care team teach you this?¬† Let me know! #diabeteseducation #type1diabetes #diabetestip #bloodsugar #t1diabetes #diabeteslife #typeonediabetic

Blood sugar taking off on airplanes? Pay attention. If you have flown with diabetes, you know how annoying the process can be: ‚úàÔ∏èyou have to take your pump off for TSA ‚úàÔ∏èthey may have to go through your bag ‚úàÔ∏èthey may have to swab your hands if the CGM picks up on the scanner ‚úàÔ∏èyou have to make sure all your prescriptions are in the right place and all your supplies are with you on your person And if that's not enough, you may need to consider dealing with a high blood sugar on the plane. There's enough stress - the last thing you need is a little bit more. One very simple thing that will help you with this is simple: making sure you get in a workout prior to your flight. Now, if you're flying at 5am, I don't know what to tell you. But, if you have a flight at a reasonable hour, by getting in some activity a few hours beforehand‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶you will boost your insulin sensitivity to help prevent you from having your blood sugar go as high as the airplane? Why? Altitude‚û°Ô∏è Stress ‚û°Ô∏è Increased blood sugars Altitude ‚û°Ô∏è¬† Dehydration ‚û°Ô∏è Increased blood sugars Dehydration ‚û°Ô∏è Increased blood sugars There's a lot of factors that could be working against you so definitely sneak in that workout, even if it's taking laps at the airport to boost that insulin sensitivity. You‚Äôll be glad you did! . . üßÅ Healthy Yellow Cupcakes üßÅ  Ingredients: - 1 1/2 cups almond flour - 1/4 cup coconut flour - 1 teaspoon baking powder - 1/2 teaspoon salt - 4 eggs - 1/2 cup unsweetened applesauce - 1/4 cup honey or maple syrup (optional for added sweetness) - 1/4 cup unsweetened almond milk - 1 teaspoon vanilla extract - Zest of 1 lemon (for a citrusy twist) Instructions: 1. Preheat the oven to 350¬∞F (175¬∞C) and line a muffin tin with cupcake liners. 2. Mix dry ingredients together in a bowl: almond flour, coconut flour, baking powder, and salt. 3. Whisk the eggs in a separate large bowl until frothy. Add the applesauce, honey (if using), almond milk, vanilla extract, and lemon zest. Mix well to combine. 4. Combine the wet and dry ingredients together and stir until just mixed. 5. Divide the batter evenly among the prepared muffin cups, filling each about two-thirds full. 6. Bake for 20-25 minutes or until a toothpick inserted into the center of a cupcake comes out clean. 7. Let them cool in the pan for 5 minutes, then transfer to a wire rack to cool completely. üíï Optional Frosting: - 1 cup cream cheese, softened - 2 tablespoons unsweetened yogurt - Sweetener to taste (like stevia or erythritol) - 1 teaspoon vanilla extract Beat all ingredients together until smooth and creamy. Spread or pipe onto cooled cupcakes. These cupcakes are lower in carbs and free from refined sugars, making them an occasional delightful treat for managing blood sugar levels. Massages will definitely help your blood sugar. I bet you never expected this one so get ready. Because I had a really jacked up hip and shoulder, it was suggested I get deep tissue massages so my body can move and function better when I train and to help with my joint mobility. I finally found an amazing massage therapist @urbanzenbodywork (a must if youre in Trampa) I started to notice a pattern every time that I left my appointment: I would also start my massage at a reasonable blood sugar, but by the time I left? My blood sugar would be trending down (!!!) The first couple times I thought this was a fluke, but then I started to think about it but it is most definitely not a fluke. Massages do good things for your blood sugars for a couple of reasons: 1. It improves your circulation and moves the lymph, helping the blood flow improve to different areas of your body. 2. It helps you to relax, so your cortisol level decreases‚Ä¶ and as a result, your blood sugars may start to drift downward. I definitely can‚Äôt be the only person who has experienced this so let me know üëáüëá Have you or will you now consider massage in your diabetes repertoire? #massagetherapy #insulindependent #typeonediabetes #diabeteseducation #t1diabetes #diabeteslife

Stop relying on Ozepmpic or Mounjaro to do all the work for you. If you live with diabetes, or even if you don‚Äôt and you are on a GLP1, it‚Äôs not all it‚Äôs cracked up to be. This can be perfectly illustrated by a patient I am working with that is on one of these medications and is having insane success. How do we define success? üî•Wt ‚¨áÔ∏è nearly 30 pounds. üî•Working out 5 days per week. üî•Food is so dialed in whether she‚Äôs at a restaurant or cooking at home. üî•Recovery on fire. Meanwhile, someone she knows (let‚Äôs call her Sally) was taking one of these medications and wasn‚Äôt seeing any sort of success. And when a mutual friend shared my patient‚Äôs success with Sally, Sally asked how she‚Äôs so successful.¬† She mentioned all the things listed above. Sally looks at her and says, ‚ÄúI do not want to do any of that.‚Äù And that is why it‚Äôs not going to work by ITSELF. If you go into taking one of these medications expecting for it to do all the work for you, it might do a little bit early on, but quite honestly? It's just a band aid covering up a deeper issue which is all the lifestyle factors. So you can decide if you want to use it as a springboard to help propel you forward, or if you want to sit here and expect it to do the work for you and then get disappointed when nothing happens. #typeonediabetes #diabeteslife #mounjaro #diabetic #insulinresistance #diabeteseducation

How diabetes travels internationally!  We are international for our 1 year anniversary and I am grateful to be able to do so! However, because of diabetes, that definitely came with its own set of challenges for packing. Here is some insight into what I did. I did switch back to my Tandem pump just from a simplicity standpoint and I have more experience with it. I packed A TON (well over double) the supplies I would need for site changes. And you‚Äôll notice I have an excessive amount of infusion sets because I‚Äôve had issues with them. I don‚Äôt want any situation where I run out of infusion sets (I‚Äôve used 6 in 6 days before). I also have backup insulin in case there‚Äôs a problem with my pump, because you don‚Äôt want a situation where you don‚Äôt have long-acting and the pump dies and now you have to rely on injections every couple of hours. Of course I‚Äôve got my meter, in case my CGM has an issue, and backup CGMs as well. Always, always, always 2-3 times what you expect you‚Äôll need because you never know what‚Äôs going to happen. Fingers crossed everything is smooth. How do you pack for your trips with diabetes? #diabeteslife #type1diabetes #diabetic #internationaltravel #t1dlookslikeme #insulinpump

This is the üí©part of diabetes that nobody sees. Let‚Äôs set the scene: It‚Äôs 12:30am in the morning, and we were supposed to be up early to head home since we were out of town. Amelia and I had gone out to a nice Italian dinner, so a high carb, high fat, high protein meal, and of course, my CGM reading was terribly off. As a result, my blood sugar starts skyrocketing because I‚Äôm using the DIY loop. The loop starts to dose, and dose, and dose because it‚Äôs concerned about my blood sugar being high. Well, once the CGM starts reading correctly, the loop realizes that it‚Äôs given way too much insulin‚Ä¶ and my blood sugar starts to plummet. So there I am at 12:30am, chowing down on candy corn that I despise, but trying to balance that with not taking too much so I don‚Äôt u-turn and fly up when the fat and protein hit‚Ä¶.¬† but also making sure I don‚Äôt take too little because I‚Äôm afraid I won‚Äôt wake up the next morning. These are the realities that we live with on a daily basis with diabetes‚Ä¶ ..and not only is it stressful, it can be downright scary. Fortunately, I was okay after this situation, but as much as I attempt to be Mr. Rose Colored Glasses with diabetes, there‚Äôs times where I have to keep it real and show the ugly side as well. #diabeteslife #typeonediabetes #t1diabetes #diabetesproblems #insulindependent #diabeticlife

Let‚Äôs play ‚Äúwho would you rather ask this to?‚Äù diabetes edition. Let‚Äôs set the scene: You‚Äôre constantly having low blood sugars during the middle to end of your workouts and they are really frustrating you. Who would you rather ask for help: a) your endocrinologist b) your diabetes educator More often than not, you are more likely to get a helpful actionable tidbit from your diabetes educator. And, as your favorite neighborhood certified diabetes educator, registered dietitian and strength coach, if you are running into this issue, the goal is to have something with a decent amount of carbs (15-25g) and a moderate amount of protein (10-20g). The protein will help steady your blood sugar and the carbs will function as a quick energy source. ¬†Because I always get asked for examples, one amazing one would be Rise protein bars. I personally love snickerdoodle, but you can‚Äôt go wrong with any of their flavors and they fit that exact mold. They‚Äôve also got a sunflower cinnamon plant-based version that is FIRE. They are convenient to throw in your bag for the next time you are training, hiking, or whatever you are doing that‚Äôs active. Having a prescription for @gvokehypopen has brought our family so much confidence and peace of mind in being prepared to treat very low blood sugar. That is why we are excited to be a part of the #LetsTalkLows campaign with @The Boggs Family | Mama and @Beyond Type 1. Ask your doctor today if it‚Äôs right for you or your loved one! #Diabetes #DiabetesAwareness #DiabetesCommunity #DiabetesLife #T1D #T2D #Type1Diabetes #Type2Diabetes #VeryLowBloodSugar #SevereHypoglycemia #GvokeHypoPen #Gvoke #LetsTalkLows What is GVOKE? GVOKE is a prescription medicine used to treat very low blood sugar (severe hypoglycemia) in people with diabetes ages 2 years and above. It is not known if GVOKE is safe and effective in children under 2 years of age. Do not use GVOKE if: you have a tumor in the gland on top of your kidneys (adrenal gland) called a pheochromocytoma, as it may cause a substantial increase in blood pressure; you have a tumor in your pancreas called an insulinoma, as it may cause low blood sugar; or if you are allergic to glucagon or any inactive ingredient in GVOKE. GVOKE may cause other serious side effects, such as serious skin rash -- in certain people with a tumor in their pancreas called a glucagonoma; Serious allergic reactions -- Call your doctor or get medical help right away if you have a serious allergic reaction including rash, difficulty breathing, low blood pressure. See Important Safety Information and Full Prescribing Information at @gvokehypopen (link in bio) US-SM-GVK-24-00060v2

Do you need Vitamin E supplements if you live with diabetes? Vitamin E is one of the fat soluble vitamins found in almonds, sunflower seeds, broccoli, spinach and other foods. Its normal benefits are improving oxidative stress (super common in diabetes), it can help your immune system work better, and even help your skin, but is it important to have? This study showed that it had a beneficial impact on people living with diabetes, decreasing A1c AND decreasing insulin resistance in a dose response fashion, showing that if you had more it usually helped a little bit better. In another study it showed between two groups (one with and one without) the group with Vitamin E improved post perineal blood sugars, blood pressure, and total cholesterol. So, there‚Äôs definitely evidence showing that it can help people living with diabetes to have better health outcomes, however, before you get too excited, you want to make sure that if you are on a blood thinner like Warfarin it actually can have adverse effects and make it even harder for your blood to clot. So please talk with your care team prior to starting it. If you‚Äôre going to start it after talking to them, start with a lower dose and work your way up. Losing weight is not the magic pill to reversing your symptoms of insulin resistance. Again, there are people who have lost weight yet still suffer from chronic illnesses such as diabetes. Diabetes is NOT a fat person disease. Is losing weight a bad intent?  Of course not ‚ÄºÔ∏è Losing weight definitely offers a lot of overall health benefits! However, don‚Äôt rely on it soley as a measure of improvement and become frustrated when the scale does not move. - This alone causes you to stress and then your blood sugar levels go ‚¨ÜÔ∏è Instead of focusing solely on weight loss, begin to focus on factors that directly affect your health (mind, spirit, emotions and choices). These include: ‚úÖ the quality of your sleep ‚úÖ the number of times you move around and not sit idle ‚úÖ keeping track of how you feel ‚úÖ keeping track of what makes you feel relaxed and not stressed ‚úÖ Identifying your triggers and managing your triggers ‚úÖ being aware of how you think about yourself Your health begins on the inside, and as a result, healing manifests and begins to reflect on the outside. Ordering food at restaurants with diabetes can be stressful. ‚Ä®Because unlike our non-diabetes friends, we have to think about every single solitary possible factor that could impact our blood sugar. üç≥ What is the portion size? üç≥What is it cooked in? üç≥Could there be hidden carb sources? üç≥Is there breading on it? üç≥Was it fried? üç≥What about he fat and protein? üç≥What if I get dessert later? These are just a FEW of the initial thoughts that go through your mind and you drive not only yourself crazy but everyone else that you go with to a restaurant crazy because they have to listen to your game of 20 questions every time you order. Recognize it doesn‚Äôt have to be super difficult. Couple things you can do: 1. Look at a menu in advance, especially if you‚Äôre in a group of people. 2. Really work on your portion estimation skills so you can have as accurate a dose as possible. 3. Make sure you‚Äôre paying attention to fat and protein later on because those are a massive deal and may not impact you on the spot but they will come back hours later without fail. Valentine‚Äôs Day candy for people living with diabetes As a registered dietitian, certified diabetes educator, and person living with diabete for over 20 year, I gotta make sure you are ready for Valentine‚Äôs Day tomorrow so you can participate in the festivities. Here‚Äôs my recommendations for you to have a sweet and delicious holiday. 1. Avoid the sugar free candy.¬† You‚Äôve seen me sound off about it before, but it does nothing except deprive you of taste, upset your stomach, and make your date sit by themselves while you spend the evening in the bathroom. 2. Pick the real candy you enjoy.¬† I personally like Reeses, so I‚Äôm going to choose Reese's hearts.¬† But if you like Milky Way, Twix, or conversation hearts, by all means do what you do. There‚Äôs no wrong answer, as long as you: 3. Portion control and dose on time.¬†¬† If you‚Äôre portion controlling and you know how much you need to dose for if you‚Äôre on insulin or how to adjust your medication and activity levels to keep your blood sugars in range, you should have no issues in participating.¬† The issue comes into play when you start going way over the top on how much you are consuming and that‚Äôs where things can become a problem. Pro tip:buy more than you need of the candies that are just sugar (for example: conversation hearts) because they will be great low snack and get them the day after the holiday. #valentinesday2024 #typeonediabetic #diabeteslife #diabeteseducator #insulindependent #sugarfreecandy #t1diabetes #diabeticfood

Does the estimated A1c from a blood sugar report = your actual A1c? (The answer may or may not make you happy) This question was asked recently by someone who was about to get their A1c drawn with their endocrinologist‚Ä¶. And they wanted to know if there were going to be any surprises.¬† There‚Äôs really two things you need to know, from my experience as both a healthcare provider in the diabetes space as well as someone who has lived with diabetes for over 20 years and uses a continuous glucose monitor: 1. Your A1c is heavily weighted towards the most recent month.¬† Yes, its overall a ‚Äúthree month average‚Äù but because it's weighted most heavily in the most recent month, it may end up a little higher or a little lower than the estimation based on what the last 30 days were.¬† If you‚Äôre running a lot higher the last 30 days, your A1c may be higher than the estimation and vice versa.¬† 2. Your CGM is reading interstitial fluid, not blood.¬† So there‚Äôs a chance that your blood sugars are not only delayed on the CGM, but the numbers may also not be accurate.¬†¬† As you‚Äôve probably seen, I‚Äôve posted times where it was off by 30, 40, 70, even 100 points at times, which means that if your sensor is consistently reading ‚Äúoff‚Äù you have a chance that your estimated A1c is not perfect. At the end of the day don‚Äôt hold fast to it.¬† Historically it tends to skew a little bit high. ‚Ä®So if your estimated A1c is 6.7, you may get an actual reading of 6.4 or 6.5. I‚Äôve seen it the other direction as well, but it's less common in my experience. So don‚Äôt treat it like the gospel. #typeonediabetes #hba1c #diabeteslife #t1diabetes #bloodsugarbalance #diabetescontrol #insulindependent

Diabetes travel hack that you NEED to know. This can be best illustrated with a story. You‚Äôre traveling to an amazing destination and you‚Äôre super excited. Let‚Äôs just pretend you‚Äôre on your way to Nashville, because everyone seems to like Nashville. You check your bag, you put your diabetes stuff in it, it goes under the plane.¬†¬† You get to Nashville and go to baggage claim‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶and your bag doesnt arrive. it turns out they lost your bag. Panic hits you. ‚ÄúHoly smokes - I don‚Äôt have ANY of my diabetes stuff.‚Äù That situation sounds terrifying, right? Instead, always store your diabetes stuff in your carry-on either under the seat in front of you or above you in the overhead bin. You want to make sure your diabetes supplies are on your person. If the airline were to lose your clothes? Not the end of the world. But if they were to lose your diabetes supplies‚Ä¶. it could be very very bad. So, low snacks and diabetes supplies under the seat in front of you - that‚Äôs what I personally do. ¬† Where do you stash your blood sugar supplies on a flight? üëáüëá PS: For more travel tips, stay tuned for the new podcast dropping very soon! #diabetestravel #traveltips #diabetictravel #diabeteslife #flighttips #thisonething

When you travel internationally you need to do this one thing (especially if you‚Äôre on an insulin pump) (This could also be applicable to traveling all the way across the United States) If you‚Äôre on an insulin pump, you know you have settings for both your basal rates and your boluses that are TIME DEPENDENT. Meaning, that at certain parts of the day, your ratios may change to help improve your blood sugar. If you‚Äôre on a system with an algorithm, that algorithm is also based on time. However, when you travel and either gain or lose time from changing time zones, that will impact how your pump is functioning and delivering insulin for you‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶which can lead to unnecessary highs and lows if you‚Äôre not careful. My recommendation?¬†¬† When you land at your final destination, change your insulin pump clock. Your body‚Äôs entire rhythm is going to be thrown out of whack as it is, but it‚Äôs 100% necessary to get the clock changed so your blood sugars can stay in range so you are staying your best and enjoying your destination. Be strict with your goals, but flexible with your methods‚ú® Sometimes, diabetes throws off our plans.  These derailments used to get me frazzled and upset. Especially when I had plans to work out and then something happened with my diabetes and I couldn‚Äôt work out like I wanted to. Or maybe I could work out, but I only had 30 minutes instead of an hour like I planned because I had to treat a low and wait for it to come up to a safe enough level to exercise before I could drive to the gym. One thing that has helped me with this is not making super rigid plans, but still some kind of rough-draft plan. For example, I have a goal of working out 3-4 days a week. On Sundays, I‚Äôll look ahead at my week and pick which 3-4 days I tentatively will work out- let‚Äôs say Mon/Weds/Fri/Sun. If something comes up with my blood sugar on Wednesday, rather than getting mad and bitter about diabetes getting in my way, I‚Äôll just say ‚Äúok so I‚Äôll move things around and workout Thursday or Saturday instead!‚Äù If I know I can‚Äôt Thursday or Saturday because I have other plans, I‚Äôll say ‚ÄúOk I‚Äôll modify and do what I can today.‚Äù Maybe that means doing an at-home workout to save time driving to-from the gym. Maybe it means shortening my workout to make it 30 minutes- you can still get a great workout in 30 minutes and something is better than nothing!! And maybe it means taking it as a sign my body needs a rest day and being ok with only working out 2-3 days that week üíú Hope this helps you today! Remember it‚Äôs all about how we respond and move forward when frustrating things happen!!! üíïüíï, Paige #type1diabeteswarriorüíô #typeonediabetic #diabeteslife

Waking up to your low alert screaming but not FEELING low? Could be a compression low. Compression lows are a common issue for people using continuous glucose monitors (CGMs). When the CGM sensor is compressed by clothing or other external factors (like rolling on it in bed during that recurring nightmare you‚Äôve been having), it can cause false low readings. It‚Äôs crucial to identify this type of pattern so that you don‚Äôt mess with your insulin dosing unnecessarily.  During my upcoming workshop, we'll practice identifying compression lows, basal variances, postprandial patterns, and more. By the end of the workshop, you'll be able to identify these patterns with ease, allowing you to respond effectively and increase your time in range. Make du‚Äôa for good health and longevity! ‚ÄúOh Allah please don‚Äôt take my soul until you are pleased with me‚Äù. When I moved into these apartments I hated these steps. My exercise routine was given to me by a special person in my life. After Fajr I drink warm lemon water and a simple floor exercise routine that targets my core. This is on my work days and off days. Then on my off days I walk the steps. I started with 5 x up the three flights and quickly went to 10x. Up and down. Are football games ruining your blood sugar? A couple weeks of NFL games are now in the books, and if you‚Äôve noticed your blood sugars running higher on Sunday afternoons than they did a couple weeks ago, then I‚Äôve got some news you‚Äôre not going to like. It is likely watching the games. I‚Äôm a Minnesota Viking fan, which means I‚Äôm CONSTANTLY on the edge of my seat‚Ä¶. ‚Ä®‚Ä®They seem to have the most ridiculous way of keeping you on the edge of your seat for both good and bad and as a result my adrenaline is through the roof (especially if I‚Äôm watching in person). As a result of that, the adrenaline causes the liver to release glucose which elevates blood sugar. Even worse, it can continue to do that throughout the entire game. Then when the game is over, your blood sugar drips all the way back down into range because there‚Äôs no adrenaline anymore. If you‚Äôre someone who puts jelly beans on the games as well (I don‚Äôt), that can just ratchet everything up even higher. And that doesn‚Äôt even factor in the wings or other snacks you may be eating as well. If you‚Äôre resistant during the game my biggest words of advice are not to overdo the correction, because when the game ends the adrenaline comes down, flight or fight goes away, and your blood sugar goes back to normal. ‚Ä®Has this happened to you? #diabeteseducation #adrenaline #typeonediabetes #insulindependent #bloodsugarmanagement #t1dlookslikeme #diabeteslife

I stayed in range during a day of international travel! Here‚Äôs how: This excursion included: ‚úàÔ∏èTwo flights ‚úàÔ∏èThree unknown meals ‚úàÔ∏èan all-nighter (I can‚Äôt sleep on planes) And travel can absolutely destroy the blood sugars of people living with diabetes, which can then impact your experience once you get to your destination. Here‚Äôs the top ways I stayed in range:‚Ä®1. I was smart with my food sources. I chose not to have any super fast-acting carbs because I was going to be sedentary. I also made sure I dosed on time, which can be easily forgotten. 2. I did activity before we flew. I had a cardio workout and I am sure that I had already reached my step goal by the time we got to the airplane so my insulin sensitivity was normal. 3. I stayed hydrated because elevation and plane rides will dehydrate you like crazy if you are not careful. 4. I made sure I got some movement in even though I was exhausted because I knew it would keep my insulin sensitivity higher. As a result, I had an amazing transition to a new time zone and was able to hit the ground running after a great night of sleep. #type1diabetes #t1diabetic #diabeteseducation #bloodsugarmanagement #insulindependent #diabeteslife

Avocados are a powerhouse food for diabetics for several reasons. They are rich in healthy fats, which can help stabilize blood sugar levels by slowing the absorption of other carbohydrates.  Additionally, avocados are low in carbohydrates, which means they have a minimal impact on blood glucose levels. They also provide a good source of fiber, which is beneficial for digestive health and can help manage blood sugar spikes. Here‚Äôs a simple and nutritious avocado toast recipe that‚Äôs perfect for diabetics: Diabetic-Friendly Avocado Toast Ingredients: - 1 ripe avocado - 2 slices of whole-grain bread - Juice of 1/2 a lemon - Salt and pepper, to taste - Optional toppings: sliced tomatoes, radish, cucumber, or a sprinkle of feta cheese Instructions: 1. Toast the whole-grain bread to your desired level of crispiness. 2. In a bowl, mash the avocado with the lemon juice, salt, and pepper. 3. Spread the mashed avocado evenly over the toasted bread. 4. Add any of the optional toppings you like. 5. Serve immediately and enjoy a delicious and blood sugar-friendly meal! This is what living with diabetes is like (and if you don‚Äôt have it, you won‚Äôt get it) Imagine this - you‚Äôre going to an important dinner at a restaurant that is new for you. You have to do an insulin pump site change before dinner because it‚Äôs time. You have some anxiety and anticipation before the dinner because it‚Äôs a really important meeting and as a result, your blood sugar starts rising a little bit. You have to consider correcting that high blood sugar, but you can‚Äôt overdo it or you‚Äôll crash at dinner, but you also can‚Äôt NOT correct or you‚Äôll keep rising. You look at the menu and you're not totally sure what to order‚Ä¶.because you're not sure what‚Äôs in the food or the size of the portion Plus, your blood sugar is already higher so you don‚Äôt want to spike even more and feel lousy. And you need to be mentally present at this dinner. Then, you have to factor in if you want alcohol, which can come back and impact your blood sugar 3-5 hours later. If you have a higher fat meal, the fat and protein can impact you hours later as well. You‚Äôre also still not sure if the reason you are rising is because of the new site or if it‚Äôs because of the anxiety. And then of course when dinner is over, if it was anxiety keeping your number high, you‚Äôre going to crash. ‚Ä® This is just scratching the surface of what people with diabetes go through on a daily basis. Yay diabetes. #diabeteslife #typeonediabetes #t1dlookslikeme #insulindependent #bloodsugar #diabetesproblems

How to not let your blood sugar ruin your day. This is a concept I embraced about 5-6 years ago and it COMPLETELY changed how I view my blood sugars. Because I would allow blood sugars to absolutely mess with my mindset AND ruin my entire day‚Ä¶.and that really robbed me of some great experiences. I call it ARM. 1. Acknowledge - Acknowledge that your blood sugar is high or low. It sucks, but you are recognizing that it is a thing. 2. Respond - What are you going to do to get this blood sugar back into range? 3. Move On - Instead of dwelling on it, just moving on with your life, focusing on the important things, and trusting that the actions you took are going to fix things for you. That is all it takes a lot of the time. 3 simple steps and suddenly your happiness is a lot higher. If you are parent of a child living with diabetes, you‚Äôll want to hear this (and if you‚Äôre currently a student in college, you‚Äôll also want to hear this) You can (and probably should) get testing accommodations. Full transparency: I had them through high school, into college, and through grad school‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶For the EXACT reason I am about to tell you. When I was in high school, I was taking a few AP exams. (those exams that give you college credit at the end of a high school course if you pass the test) I had applied for accommodations and, thankfully, had gotten them. I was able to: ‚úèÔ∏ètake my test in a separate room ‚úèÔ∏è stop the clock as I needed to for breaks ‚úèÔ∏èI could have food and drink in case my number was low or high ‚úèÔ∏è I had the ability to take bathroom breaks So what happens during the AP English Language test? My blood sugar ended up going to 43‚Ä¶ I ended up having to stop the clock for almost an hour as I waited for my blood sugar to come back up‚Ä¶ Most of these tests have really stringent rules where if you leave the room your test is disqualified or you lose a bunch of time. So either way, it would have put me at a massive disadvantage. You may have to work in conjunction with your school and/or the testing organization in order to get accommodations, but in the situation you need them, it‚Äôs better to have them and not need them than need them and not have them. #diabeteslife #diabeteseducation #insulindependent #t1dlookslikeme #diabetesadvocate #lowbloodsugar

Managing hypoglycemia can be a tricky business. There are many factors that can contribute to low blood sugar, including physical activity, stress, medications, and missing meals. When you experience hypoglycemia, your body needs a quick source of glucose to bring your blood sugar levels back up. However, not all treatments for low blood sugar are created equal. Liquid, powders, and gels are going to be the fastest. Avoid foods with fiber, protein, and fat when treating hypoglycemia.  If your belly is digesting more slowly, make sure to choose glucose tablets or gel because these dissolve in your mouth first. If you‚Äôre unable to swallow or are incoherent, a glucagon injection or inhalant should be used. Type 1 diabetes is a lifelong, auto-immune condition in which the body stops producing insulin, which is a hormone, necessary for regulating blood sugar levels. Managing diabetes requires a lot of hard work and dedication. For those diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes, they often face an emotional struggle, dealing with the realities of the disease. People with diabetes often have to deal with the physical, psychological, social and financial impact of the disease. Physically, diabetes brings a range of physical challenges. People with diabetes have to constantly manage blood sugar levels which can be difficult and time consuming. They have to track their foods, test their blood sugar levels, and adjust their medication, if needed. This kind of daily routine can cause diabetes burn out, which can lead to feelings of frustration and exhaustion. Psychologically, Type 1 diabetes can cause feelings of depression, hopelessness and loneliness. People with Type 1 may have a hard time staying motivated and focused to manage their diabetes, especially in times of high stress or when their diabetes isn't under control. They may also feel a sense of guilt or shame about their diagnosis, which can be difficult to overcome. Socially, living with diabetes can be isolating. People with diabetes may not be able to participate in everyday activities or access social support in the same way as others. They may also feel like their diabetes is an obstacle, preventing them from enjoying their lives like others. Finally, there is a financial impact of diabetes. Managing diabetes can be expensive, as it requires medications, doctor visits, lab tests and supplies.  It is important to recognize that managing diabetes can be difficult and emotional, and it is important to reach out for help if you need it. There are a variety of resources to help with the psychological and emotional aspects of diabetes, such as support groups, counselling sessions, online communities and books. #diabetes #diabetesawareness #diabetestypel #diabetestype2 #diabetesmanagement #diabetessucks #diabetesdiet #diabetesprevention #diabetestreatment #diabeteslife #diabetessupport

Living with Type 1 Diabetes can be challenging, but with the right knowledge and tools, it is possible to achieve optimal management and better health. Here are 7 essential steps to help guide your journey. First and foremost, educate yourself about diabetes, its causes, symptoms, and treatment options. Regularly monitor your blood sugar levels to ensure they stay within a healthy range. Pay close attention to your nutrition, focusing on a balanced diet that includes whole grains, lean proteins, and plenty of fruits and vegetables. Regular exercise is crucial for managing diabetes, so find activities that suit your preferences and make them a part of your routine. Consistently take your prescribed medications as directed by your healthcare provider. Seek support from friends, family, and support groups to stay motivated and informed. Lastly, practice mindfulness techniques such as meditation or deep breathing exercises to reduce stress and improve overall well-being. By incorporating these essential steps into your daily life, it is possible to master Type 1 Diabetes and achieve optimal health. #Type1DiabetesManagement #HealthyLiving #diabetestype1 #diabeteslife

Let's separate fact from fiction with these 5 eye-opening points! üí• üî¨ Fact #1: Genetics are not the sole cause of diabetes. While family history can increase your risk, lifestyle factors such as diet and exercise are equally important in prevention and management. üç∞ Fact #2: It's not just about avoiding sugar. Carbohydrate intake also matters! Monitoring and balancing your carbohydrate consumption is crucial for people with diabetes, as carbohydrates directly impact blood sugar levels. ü•ñ Fact #3: Diabetes goes beyond type 1 and type 2. Did you know that type 2 diabetes can be reversible? By adopting a healthy lifestyle, including regular physical activity and a balanced diet, many individuals have successfully managed to reverse their type 2 diabetes. üåü Fact #4: There is no magic cure for diabetes. While insulin is commonly used to manage blood sugar levels, it is not a cure. Let's set the record straight not all carbohydrates cause type 2 diabetes. Complex carbs play a crucial role in a healthy, balanced diet. Complex carbs, found in whole grains, fruits and vegetables, are rich in fibre, vitamins and minerals. They provide sustained energy and support digestion. Refined carbs, such as white bread, sugary treats and processed foods, have undergone processing trust removes essential nutrients and fibre. Consuming excessive refined carbs, combined with a high intake of saturated fats, can lead to insulin resistance at a cellular level.

Teriyaki chicken - over 40g of protein and only 14g of carbs (and 13g of fat), this is probably the best looking option from a nutritional perspective on the menu with a good amount of protein and relatively tame amount of carbs (you could do way worse) 2. Wok fried shrimp - 17g of protein and 19g of carbs - as long as your dose is on point, you get a decent amount of protein for a snack. 3. Black pepper angus beef - Another solid snack option with a good amount of protein (19g) with only 13g of carbs..¬† I would be very careful with the rice, since white rice will spike your blood sugar very, very quickly if you‚Äôre not on point with the dosing or the portion size. Safety Exerice Tips For Diabetes on Beta Blockers  If you're managing diabetes and are prescribed insulin or sulfonylureas, it's crucial to be aware of the potential risks when taking beta blockers. Beta blockers, commonly used to treat various medical conditions, can increase the risk of experiencing "silent" hypoglycemia - low blood sugar without noticeable symptoms. üö¶ Why does this happen? Beta blockers can mask the typical warning signs of low blood sugar, such as shakiness, sweating, and rapid heartbeat. This makes it essential for individuals with diabetes on these medications to monitor their blood sugar levels regularly. #diabetescontrol #juvenilediabetes #diabetescare #exerciseforheartdisease #curediabetes #type2diabetes #diabetesreversal #typeonediabetes #heartdiseaseawareness #diabetesexercise #diabetesmedication #diabetestips #diabetesgym #diabetesdoesntstopme #diabetestype1 #diabetesmanagement #diabetesfitness #diabetescomplications #heartdisease #diabetes10k #diabetestipo2 #hearthealth #diabetescure #diabetessucks #diabeteslife #diabetesexercises #type1diabetes #diabetesawareness #diabetessupplies #diabetessymptoms

Difference Between Type1 and Type 2 Diabetes: What You Need to know in 60sec Diabetes is a metabolic disorder characterized by elevated blood glucose levels, which can lead to a multitude of health complications. It's essential to comprehend that while both type 1 and type 2 diabetes share the common feature of high blood sugar, they are fundamentally distinct conditions. üîµ Type 1 Diabetes: Typically presents during childhood or adolescence, although adult-onset cases are infrequent. It originates from an autoimmune response within the body, resulting in the destruction of pancreatic beta cells responsible for insulin production. Individuals with type 1 diabetes necessitate lifelong insulin therapy due to their inability to naturally produce this hormone. üî¥ Type 2 Diabetes: Predominantly associated with insulin resistance, where the body's tissues exhibit reduced responsiveness to circulating insulin. Concurrently, the pancreas struggles to produce an adequate quantity of insulin to counteract this resistance. In response, the pancreas may escalate insulin secretion, eventually leading to a state of beta-cell dysfunction. No sugar coating here. Let‚Äôs talk about high blood sugar and diabetes. In type one diabetes, which is often genetic, individuals do not produce enough insulin needed to process sugar.  While in type two diabetes, our bodies develop a resistance to insulin, which then causes our blood sugar to be high. If you are checking your blood sugar prior to eating anything for the day, it should be between 70 to 100.   If your blood sugar is high, then consider asking your doctor for a hemoglobin a1c test. A normal hemoglobin a1c is 5.7 or lower.  While a hemoglobin a1c of 6.5 or higher indicates a possible diagnosis of diabetes. Eating complex starches, such as wheat bread and sweet potatoes verses white bread and white potatoes helps in managing blood sugar. Every adult, 35 years and older should get screened for diabetes. Check your blood sugar today. #diabetes #diabetesawareness #diabeteslife #doctor #healthylifestyles #healthymindset #foodasmedicine

I loved @thehangrywoman 's recent post about her 2022 healthcare costs and wanted to share mine.  Imagine all the things I could've done with this money? Money that an able bodied person didn't need to spend on insulin, CGMs, pump supplies, MD visits, and the more expensive insurance plan I'm offered by an employer.  Now, also consider the fact that I'm a privileged lady with access to decent health insurance and a well paying job.  In 2021, roughly 30 million Americans of all ages were not insured. Many more were underinsured (as in their insurance won't cover what they need to survive).  If MY yearly out of pocket cost is close to $10,000, you can only imagine the struggle for someone who isn't insured or who is underinsured.   If this makes you angry (as it should), visit @t1internation to see how you can help advocate for accessible insulin for all. . . . . . #t1d #diabetic #type1diabetes #insulin #diabadass #typeonediabetes #diabetesawareness #type1diabetic #bloodsugar #diabetestype1 #bloodglucose #t1dlookslikeme #diabetes #diabetesmanagement  #diabetesessentials #diabeteslife #diabetescommunity #womenwithdiabetes #insulin4all #medicareforall

Confession: I neglected a major part of my diabetes life this past month and a half You may remember a stat where if you did every ‚Äúsingle thing you have to do to live a healthy life with diabetes every day‚Äù, it would take you over three hours per day. One of those things? checking your feet. People with diabetes don‚Äôt have the greatest circulation due to blood sugars bouncing, therefore, nutrient flow is slower to the extremities. So if you get cracks or cuts ok your feet or heels, you may be less likely to notice until it's too late‚Ä¶and they can get infected. I have not been checking my feet between work, traveling, training, and other things I have been involved in. That being said, my feet got way too dry and calloused to the point they actually hurt.  To get myself in a better spot, I‚Äôm looking for the thing that will do it the fastest. ‚Ä®The fastest thing I have found that might be beneficial to you if you‚Äôve been neglecting yours as well, is the Lavior diabetic foot creme. ‚Ä®Because it‚Äôs specific to people living with diabetes, it‚Äôs formulated to help get the moisture in faster and heal anything that may have happened already‚Ä¶so ideally you are in a stage of prevention. I swear by this stuff. Do you maintain your feet health? #typeonediabetes #diabeteslife #diabetestype1 #type1diabetes #diabeticfriendly #diabeteseducation

If you ONLY listened to your endo, the ONLY nutrient you‚Äôd ever have to worry about is CARBS, right?‚Å£ ‚Å£ When you get diagnosed, the FIRST thing you are told is:‚Å£ ‚Å£ LOOK OUT FOR CARBS SINCE YOU HAVE DIABEETUS¬† ‚Å£ ‚Å£ Then,‚Å£ ‚Å£ 1. Start counting your carbs at each meal.‚Å£ ‚Å£ 2. Start dosing based on carbs.‚Å£ ‚Å£ It‚Äôs as though the educators forget there are other nutrients that can impact your blood sugars as much‚Ä¶if not MORE than carbs‚Å£ ‚Å£ They can work in tandem WITH carbs to potentially wreak HAVOC‚Ä¶‚Å£ ‚Å£ Or, to stabilize your blood sugars.‚Å£ ‚Å£ But, you gotta know how to use them.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Who are they?‚Å£ ‚Å£ Protein and fat.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Both of them have their own unique ways of raising your blood sugar.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Their effects can also be delayed!‚Å£ ‚Å£ Not many educators or dietitians are talking about this.‚Å£ ‚Å£ This is SO important.‚Å£ ‚Å£ You have to take into consideration all of the nutrients because all of them will impact your blood sugars..‚Å£ ‚Å£ Having that understanding is absolutely crucial to having complete food freedom‚Å£ ‚Å£ While having amazing blood sugars.‚Å£ #type1diabetes #diabeteseducation #t1diabetes #diabetesdiet #bloodsugarmanagement #diabeticfriendly #diabeteslife

What i‚Äôd order at 5 guys as a registered dietitian, certified diabetes educator, person living with type 1 diabetes. Full transparency, I‚Äôve never eaten here, but here we are and it‚Äôs TOUGH: 1. Get the burger, it‚Äôs got 18g of protein and consider ditching half the bun to reduce the carbs. 2. Load that burger up with lettuce, pickles, tomatoes, onions, mushrooms, peppers‚Ä¶any veggies you can get will definitely help sneak a serving of veggies in there. 3. If you‚Äôre really looking to go lower carb, then skip the bun entirely, add bacon and cheese adding up to 30g of protein, which will still have fat and impact you later, but will have minimal impact to your blood sugar compared to the alternative. 4. If you‚Äôre going to get the fries, share the small. The small is 72g of carbs - that is a lot of fries for any one individual. 5. If you must do a shake, share it. This is what living with diabetes is like Picture this:¬† you're going out to dinner with your significant other or your friend.¬† You go to the restaurant.¬† It‚Äôs a fantastic Italian place.¬† You‚Äôre looking at the menu, you see a pasta dish with a cream sauce that looks incredible, there‚Äôs a steak based dish, there‚Äôs calamari‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶it all looks incredible. Before anything else, you have to think about:‚Ä® üçïhow many carbs your going to dose for üçïhow much fat your going to have to factor in üçïwhen is that fat going to hit your blood sugar later on üçïis the protein going to have any impact on your blood sugar¬† But before you can even dose that you realize, ‚Äúwait, we walked a mile to this restaurant so I need to factor that into the dosing so I don‚Äôt crash on the way home‚Äù... ‚Äúwere going to go into the hot tub after this too, which can also potentially make my blood sugars get a little wonky from the heat and insulin working faster‚Ä¶.‚Äù ‚ÄúWAIT, what if we then get spontaneous dessert after the fact, which is only an hour and a half from now, and then‚Ä¶‚Äù You start to see how you have to literally have to live in the moment, but also live five minutes, fifty minutes, and 500 minutes into the future. I joke that you don‚Äôt understand diabetes unless you live with it or live with someone who has it (even then you kinda get it cause you don‚Äôt know what the high and low blood sugars feel like) But if this doesn‚Äôt describe diabetes to a T, I don‚Äôt know what does. #typeonediabetes #diabetic #t1diabetes #diabeteslife #insulindependent #bloodsugars

I don‚Äôt put my CGM into body fat‚Ä¶here‚Äôs why‚Ä®‚Ä®The placement of your CGM matters‚Ä¶ until it absolutely does not. Many times in diabetes, especially if you‚Äôre on an insulin pump, you‚Äôre used to always putting your site into what is known as subcutaneous tissue, which is otherwise known as body fat. (Yes, it‚Äôs more technical than that, but we‚Äôll use it as body fat for this example) However, I can count on one hand the number of times I have put my Dexcom somewhere that is not my stomach. I put my Dexcom on my stomach where I am pretty lean. ‚Ä®Here‚Äôs the reasons why: 1. Your CGM is not pumping any liquid into you like an insulin pump would be.¬†¬† It‚Äôs just reading interstitial fluid to give you a blood sugar reading. Because of that, as long as the site doesn‚Äôt hurt and has a clear signal to the device (to your phone or receiver) it is perfectly fine. 2. Because insulin pumps or injections can create so much scar tissue, and this device is not pumping into my body, less scar tissue is formed and I don‚Äôt have to eat into the areas of subcutaneous tissue that I do have that would be better served for my pump sites and injections. This may be an unpopular opinion but it‚Äôs worked for me and I don‚Äôt plan on stopping any time soon. Fortunately I don‚Äôt put sites or injections into my arm. #continuousglucosemonitor #type1diabetic #bloodsugars #t1dlookslikeme #diabeteseducator #diabeteslife

3 things I NEVER travel without as a person with diabetes It‚Äôs starting to get towards that time of year where you may be traveling for warmer weather, spring break vacation, or even just a long weekend away with your family. But as people with diabetes, we very much need to consider the preparation ahead of time to be successful. Here‚Äôs 3 things I never travel without: 1. Extra CGM monitor tape.¬†  It‚Äôs hard enough to travel with enough diabetes supplies, but lord forbid that your supplies fail because you are in a warmer climate, or go into a pool, and your adhesive doesn‚Äôt work and now you don‚Äôt have a continuous glucose monitor anymore.¬† I sweat A TON so this tape saves me. 2. Lavior diabetic first aid gel. Especially if you are into outdoor activities, this one is huge. But even if you‚Äôre not, the last thing you want is to be enjoying your trip and you get a nasty scrape or cut that you need to heal as fast as possible. This stuff is the best out there. It‚Äôs formulated specifically for people living with diabetes, It‚Äôs super easy to work with, and it makes the healing process exponentially faster. 3. Refillable water bottle.¬† May seem super basic, but hydration is one of those things that you forget about constantly when you are in the middle of having a great time.¬† Given you are already out of routine and your food may be different than normal, your blood sugars have the potential to run higher and being hydrated will help prevent you from ending up with an even nastier blood sugar situation.¬†  Plus, if you‚Äôre in a warmer climate it‚Äôs good to stay on top of your water intake. UNPOPULAR OPINION ALERTüö®‚Å£ ‚Å£ You‚Äôve heard of the rule of 15 right?‚Å£ ‚Å£ When your blood sugar is low, you take 15g of fast-acting glucose or a carb source.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Then, you wait 15 minutes before you re-test and see what your blood sugar is.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Problem is? This doesn't work for ALL situations.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Why?‚Å£ ‚Å£ 15 carbs may not be enough for everyone‚Äôs blood sugar‚Å£ It may be too much for some lows (especially for kids)‚Å£ Waiting fifteen minutes may not be enough‚Å£ ‚Å£ There are plenty of other reasons I could share here.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Recognize this: EVERYONE is different and EVERY low blood sugar is different‚Ä¶‚Å£ ‚Å£ So, they are all going to be treated a little bit differently.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Ultimately you have to figure out what is going to work best for you based on the activity you are doing, based on the severity of your low, based on active insulin, and so many other factors.‚Å£ ‚Å£ Make sure you have a plan for your lows #lowbloodsugar #t1diabetes #hypoglycemia #diabeteslife #typeonediabetes #diabeteseducation

This is what living with diabetes is like (If you don‚Äôt know and don‚Äôt live with it you aren‚Äôt going to understand this) Let‚Äôs set the stage: You‚Äôre at a sporting event and you‚Äôre feeling hungry and go to the concession stand for some food.¬† Instead of simply ordering you need to:‚Ä®‚Ä®üíÄFigure out how many carbs are in the food you are getting. This can be a challenge since there‚Äôs no label or nutritional information. üíÄConsider the fat and protein that may hit you hours later. This can impact your choice of food that you want to eat.¬† üíÄYou get ready to dose, but realize you‚Äôre a little over halfway through the game and your insulin will still be active when the game is over. üíÄAfter the game you're about to walk a little over a mile to get back to where you're staying, so you can‚Äôt take too much now, or you‚Äôll go low, but you can‚Äôt take too little or you‚Äôll sit through the rest of the game with a high blood sugar. üíÄOnce you get there, you have to consider that you may change and go get a legit meal in about an hour or two, when the fat may hit, so you have to factor that in. üíÄIt‚Äôs also hot outside, so the temperature may make you more insulin sensitive. Massages will definitely help your blood sugar. I bet you never expected this one so get ready. Because I had a really jacked up hip and shoulder, it was suggested I get deep tissue massages so my body can move and function better when I train and to help with my joint mobility. I finally found an amazing massage therapist @urbanzenbodywork (a must if youre in Trampa) I started to notice a pattern every time that I left my appointment: I would also start my massage at a reasonable blood sugar, but by the time I left? My blood sugar would be trending down (!!!) The first couple times I thought this was a fluke, but then I started to think about it but it is most definitely not a fluke. Massages do good things for your blood sugars for a couple of reasons: 1. It improves your circulation and moves the lymph, helping the blood flow improve to different areas of your body. 2. It helps you to relax, so your cortisol level decreases‚Ä¶ and as a result, your blood sugars may start to drift downward. I definitely can‚Äôt be the only person who has experienced this so let me know üëáüëá Have you or will you now consider massage in your diabetes repertoire? #massage #diabetescare #type1diabetes #diabetic #diabetes #diabeteslife #massagetherapy #bloodsugar

Why to not IMMEDIATELY rush to correct a low blood sugar: Not too long ago, I went out to dinner with Amelia to one of our favorite places and it was nothing short of delicious. We were out of town, so we had to walk back to our hotel. I had just eaten a lot of food‚Ä¶.. ‚Ä¶A lot of food to the tune of 11 active units in my system. And of course, since we had to walk back about a mile back to our hotel, you would expect that walking is going to make that insulin far more potent and make my blood sugar crash‚Ä¶. Before leaving, my blood sugar was in the low 200s. However, by the time we got back to the hotel¬† about 20 minutes later, I was already shooting down and borderline low. But, I did not immediately treat that low‚Ä¶. And, to my non-surprise, my blood sugar came back up all by itself.¬†¬† Had I treated that low, I would have gone super high. You might be thinking ‚ÄúBen, you‚Äôre crazy, why would you not treat a low?‚Äù Because, had I treated the low, I would have shot up SUPER fast‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶because when I left the restaurant my blood sugar was still trending up. Meaning, my body was still starting to digest. When I start walking, the blood flow is now going to my legs and to my arms as opposed to my digestion system‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶so I‚Äôm not digesting any more carbs - and digestion is on pause. Then, when we got back to our hotel, digestion started up again and the food started kicking in once again. So, while I‚Äôm not advocating for you to not treat low blood sugar (quite the opposite, honestly), I am advocating for you to look at ALL of the possible factors as to what is going on‚Ä¶ BEFORE you make a rash treatment decision because sometimes you can overdo it really quickly. Has this happened to you before? #lowbloodsugar #diabetesproblems #lifewithdiabetes #type1 #diabetic #type1diabetes #bloodsugar #diabeteslife #moveyourbody #alilbitcrazy #diabetesdietitian #dietitiansoftiktok

When I‚Äôm in the mood for fried rice I make this dish, which gives me the Asian flavor without spiking insulin levels. Here‚Äôs what you need: 1-2 heads of cauliflower (you can buy this pre-chopped) 5-6 scallions 4 cloves garlic 1 TBSP ginger (I use fresh ginger; it makes a difference) 1/2 cup cashews 1/2 cup carrots (I hate peas so I don‚Äôt use them) 2 eggs 2-3 TBSP soy sauce (I use Braggs Amino acids instead) Red pepper flakes 1 TBSP Rice vinegar 1 TBSP Sesame oil 2-3 TBSP Vegetable oil Salt to taste  Chop everything first because things move fast once you get going. Separate the white and green parts of the scallions.  Heat vegetable oil; add white part of scallions, garlic and ginger. After a couple of minutes, add cauliflower then carrots. Stir well. Add Braggs (or soy sauce), rice vinegar, sesame oil. Stir well. Scramble eggs and add along with cashews and green scallions. And there you go! I was 5 years old when I was diagnosed with diabetes, and when I returned to school, my teacher awarded me with the character word of the month: Resilience.  It was profound even for my tiny brain at the time. It has followed me and served me well throughout my life. The ability to withstand and move forward from difficulties.
