Cristina was readmitted into the hospital Friday and has since been released. It may take a couple of days for her to recover as her immune system is weak but we are hopeful in a few days she will be back on track for her post op healing. We are thankful for her GJ tube as we can keep her hydrated and give her meds that she needs. We are also extremely thankful for her Dexcom. Dexcom has continued to be spot on for the most part and has caught Cristina‚Äôs lows and highs. Last night Dexcom alerted to Cristina being low. At first I thought it needed to be calibrated because she had just eaten an hour before. But Cristina never shows signs of being low or high until we are so far out of range we are having to take major steps. Because Dexcom alerted to the low, I checked her glucose to verify it thinking it would just need to be calibrated. But it was spot on. Cristina dropped as low as 40. Because of Dexcom alerting us to the low, we were able to have the doctor working with us as we were actively treating her low and making adjustments. As she continued to drop and the alarms kept going off, the doctor was able to work with us to not only treat the low but to also suspend her insulin temporarily and then once she came back up, to adjust her basal rate to get her levels under better control. Lows aren‚Äôt easy to deal with but I am just so thankful for the technology we have and that we can heavily rely on it to alert us to a problem as it starts and as it‚Äôs resolving. We are exhausted to say the least but Cristina made it to pet therapy today so that‚Äôs a win we are celebrating. #transplantsurgery #tpiat #type3cdiabetic #type1diabetes #diabetes #postop #hospital #dexcom #t1diabetes #lowglucose #lowbloodsugar #therapypet #fyp #foryoupage #AXERatioChallenge #diabeteslife #dexcomg6

Balanced Blood Sugar Roadmap Testimonial: Scott Today, I‚Äôm here to share another amazing client success story! I‚Äôve been working with Scott for the last few months who came to me with higher blood sugar, low energy, and digestive symptoms when introducing new foods. Initially, we worked on stabilizing his blood sugar with a personalized nutrition and movement plan during the day so that when he did have carbs, it didn‚Äôt spike on him. After building up his foundation, we ran what‚Äôs called a Full Monty panel, which shows iron in relation to other minerals. We found multiple iron levels to be high, which in excess can be problematic. Excess iron can promote the liver to kick out extra glucose into the bloodstream (hello high fasting blood sugars), increase insulin resistance, is food for bad bacteria, which lower immunity and promote gut issues, and lowers metabolism increasing the likelihood of energy issues. After discussing these results, we looked at incorporating food and supplements to help lower the impact of this iron, including food-based sources of vitamin C, copper, and vitamin A and supplemental IP6. By focusing on these nutrients in addition to the lifestyle he had created, Scott not only saw his blood sugar balance improve, but his energy and digestion improved too.  This speaks to the importance of not just eating healthy to support your blood sugar, but also balancing your body‚Äôs minerals so they can bring out all the qualities of good health. If you would like some help with this too, message me ‚ÄúSupport‚Äù and we can talk more about your goals! . . #bloodsugarbalance #insulinresistance #diabetescare #diabetessupport #balancednutrition #diabeteslife #diabetesjourney

This woman was telling me how she would go to bed after dinner with a blood sugar in the 120s‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶but she would wake up every single morning at 225 - and she had no idea why. Her number would just start climbing in the middle of the night, for seemingly NO REASON‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶.and it would drive her crazy.¬†¬† She would wake up the next morning feeling like garbage.¬†¬† It‚Äôs typically attributed to fat and protein (but predominantly fat) kicking in hours after a meal.¬† The first step in conquering it is being AWARE of it. If you notice that certain meals are causing you to wake up with a high blood sugar despite going to bed at a normal number, take a look at that fat content and ask yourself, is this a meal that could have done that? Yes, this is probably the #1 most discussed and worked on topic within our team‚Äôs work with the diabetes community. But no, it is not super simple cut and dry - it must be personalized for every single person for their situation and their needs. Let's talk about Type 2 diabetes and the misconception surrounding its curability! üö´ü©∫ It's time to break the stigma and shed some light on this important topic. üí° Many people believe that Type 2 diabetes is incurable, but let's dive deeper into what "cure" really means. ü§î Imagine a balloon that can only hold a certain amount of air. If you keep blowing more air into it, eventually, it will burst. In our bodies, this bursting manifests as metabolic dysfunction, which is what we experience with diabetes. üí• Curing diabetes doesn't mean you can go back to overindulging in unhealthy habits. Instead, it involves finding the right balance and taking control of your lifestyle. üå± Here are some key steps to managing and potentially achieving control over Type 2 diabetes: ü•ó Maintain a low-calorie intake: A healthy, balanced diet plays a crucial role in managing diabetes. Focus on nutrient-rich foods, portion control, and reducing sugar and processed foods. ‚è∞ Practice time-restricted feeding: Consider implementing a pattern of eating within specific time windows, allowing your body to effectively process and utilize the nutrients. üèãÔ∏è Engage in physical activity and exercise: Regular exercise not only aids in recovery but also helps manage blood sugar levels and improve overall well-being. Find activities you enjoy and make them part of your routine. üíä Strive for minimal medication reliance: While some individuals may still require medication support, the ultimate goal is to reduce the dosage and effectively manage diabetes through lifestyle changes. This is one of my biggest diabetes pet peeves üö® (This was not based on Amelia, thank the lord.) There is NOTHING worse than when someone who has zero qualifications to be telling you what to do with your diabetes‚Ä¶. And tries to tell you exactly what YOU need to do to keep YOUR health in check. In this case, it is a significant other that means well, but they have no medical background and should not be giving any insight on how to best manage blood sugars.¬†¬† However, because they are a significant other, they may believe they are entitled to tell you these things. To avoid these situations from over-eager partners, I would DEFINITELY encourage you to sit down early on in the relationship and discuss boundaries surrounding your diabetes and their involvement. Because you don‚Äôt want to end up in a situation like this and you don‚Äôt want diabetes to become a point of contention. #diabetesawareness #datingwithdiabetes #diabetes #ididntaskyou #significantother #diabeticlife #diabeteslife #tiktokdiabetes

The average person with diabetes is making 180 unique decisions about their management each day. (That‚Äôs 177 more than what you just saw in this video) Let that sink in for a second. Assuming you are awake for 16 hours of the day, that is a decision every FIVE MINUTES to keep your blood sugars in range and your health in check. It can seem like a lot. And sometimes, out of those 180 decisions you might make the wrong decision. Your blood sugar may end up high, your blood sugar may end up low. And ultimately that‚Äôs okay. Don‚Äôt beat yourself up about it and give yourself a little bit of grace. The key is learning from those decisions and second doing your best to get more and more efficient with the decisions every single day. Eventually, once you have the right framework in place on the nutrition, exercise, and daily management of things, these 180 decisions might feel like a handful and are no big deal. #diabetescare #diabetesmanagement #diabeticlife #diabeteslife #t1d

This food is not blood sugar friendly‚Ä¶. no matter what the packaging tries to tell you. The best way to illustrate this is with a story. Once upon a time, one of my patients Billy came across this exact snack.¬† ‚Ä® He figured ‚Äúit's low in carbs, so it shouldn‚Äôt impact my blood sugar; it‚Äôs sweet and should taste good‚Äù and he was really excited to try it. He tried them, started out with a blood sugar of 126 before experiencing a WHOOSH! There went the blood sugar‚Ä¶. From 126 to 262 with an up arrow¬† on his continuous glucose monitor which was very concerning to himüò≥ He had to correct, and correct, and correct again before it finally started to budge. Billy ultimately¬† got frustrated and threw away the rest of the box because he felt like it was all a lie. No one was able to explain it to him until we discussed what I‚Äôm about to tell you. In this case, Billy‚Äôs snack had a ton of prebiotic soluble fiber‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶ related cousins of tapioca fiber, soluble corn fiber, or IMOs. All of those things that are in many of these ‚Äúlower carb‚Äù processed foods will actually get absorbed at about 83% of the rate of a simple sugar, maltose. And you know what simple sugars do, right? Skyrocket blood sugars.üöÄ Meaning, if you‚Äôre subtracting fiber from these foods to consider them as net carbs, you are going to be shooting yourself in the foot. The moral of the story here is what we tell our patients: just¬† eat the real thing. ¬†Enjoy the real food and stop messing around with these other synthetic versions that aren‚Äôt going to be beneficial to your blood sugar or to your taste buds. #diabeteseducation #typeonediabetes #t1diabetes #diabeteslife #insulindependent #highbloodsugar #diabetestype1

As a Type 1 diabetic, one strategy that really helps me stabilize my blood sugar throughout the day is keeping my meals as consistent as possible in terms of protein, carbs, and fats. Here‚Äôs why this approach works so well for me: üìä Predictable Blood Sugar Response: By eating meals with similar macronutrient ratios, I can better predict how my body will respond. This predictability makes it easier to manage my insulin doses and avoid unexpected blood sugar spikes or drops. ü•ó Balanced Nutrition: Consistently balanced meals ensure I‚Äôm getting the right mix of nutrients. Protein helps with muscle repair and keeps me full, carbs provide essential energy, and healthy fats support overall health. This balance helps maintain steady energy levels throughout the day. üõ°Ô∏è Improved Insulin Management: When my meals are consistent, it simplifies insulin management. I can adjust my insulin doses more accurately because I know what to expect from each meal. This reduces the guesswork and stress associated with blood sugar management. üìÖ Routine and Simplicity: Establishing a meal routine simplifies my daily life. I don‚Äôt have to constantly calculate and adjust for varying food compositions, which saves time and reduces anxiety about managing my diabetes. üçΩÔ∏è Practical Examples: For breakfast, I might have Greek yogurt with berries and a sprinkle of nuts every day. Lunch could be a salad with grilled chicken, quinoa, and avocado. Dinner might be a balanced plate of fish, sweet potatoes, and steamed vegetables. Keeping these meals consistent helps me stay on track. üåü Takeaway: If you‚Äôre a Type 1 diabetic, consider trying consistent meal compositions. It‚Äôs not about eating the same foods all the time but maintaining similar macronutrient ratios to stabilize blood sugar levels effectively. #Type1Diabetes #BloodSugarControl #ConsistentMeals #HealthyEating #DiabetesManagement #BalancedNutrition #DiabetesLife #StabilizeBloodSugar #WellnessJourney #HealthyHabits #FeelGoodLiveBetter

Omnipod vs. Tandem - which insulin pump did I choose? As you may know I have been a long time user of Tandem insulin pump (but I don‚Äôt use Control IQ). However, last fall, I wanted to try something a little different, so I was fortunate enough to switch over to the Omnipod to try the tubeless experience (and eventually try the DIY loop). I have kept you up to date with my Omnipod experience (and have been loving it), but having used both for a substantial amount of time my final verdict is (drumroll please): Tandem. Here‚Äôs the thing - I love them both. You can‚Äôt go wrong with either one. But the main reason I would lean toward Tandem is simply because of MY body. Not from the systems themselves. As you may recall, I have a lot of issues with my sites hitting scar tissue and then not absorbing.¬† Everytime that happens for the Omnipod, I have to replace the entire pod, and I typically lose the majority of the insulin. On the flip side with Tandem, I can just switch out the infusion set without losing any insulin. For that reason alone, I would be selecting Tandem right now, but I plan to switch back and forth depending on the activity I‚Äôm going to be doing. If you are uncertain between the two, you cannot go wrong with either option - just pick what is best for YOUR situation. #omnipoddash #type1diabetes #diabeteslife #tandemdiabetes #insulinpump #diabetestype1 #bloodsugarmanagement #diabeteseducation

For more traveling with diabetes tips, check out the link in @gvokehypopen bio! @The Boggs Family | Mama  #Diabetes #DiabetesAwareness #DiabetesCommunity #DiabetesLife #T1D #T2D #Type1Diabetes #Type2Diabetes #VeryLowBloodSugar #SevereHypoglycemia #GvokeHypoPen #Gvoke What is GVOKE? GVOKE is a prescription medicine used to treat very low blood sugar (severe hypoglycemia) in people with diabetes ages 2 years and above. It is not known if GVOKE is safe and effective in children under 2 years of age. Do not use GVOKE if: you have a tumor in the gland on top of your kidneys (adrenal gland) called a pheochromocytoma, as it may cause a substantial increase in blood pressure; you have a tumor in your pancreas called an insulinoma, as it may cause low blood sugar; or if you are allergic to glucagon or any inactive ingredient in GVOKE. GVOKE may cause other serious side effects, such as serious skin rash -- in certain people with a tumor in their pancreas called a glucagonoma; Serious allergic reactions -- Call your doctor or get medical help right away if you have a serious allergic reaction including rash, difficulty breathing, low blood pressure. See Important Safety Information and Full Prescribing Information @gvokehypopen (link in bio).   US-GVK-24-00105

I have switched to the Omnipod for a few weeks - here‚Äôs my thoughts! After spending over 20 years on an insulin pump with a tube attached to me, I‚Äôve finally been trying the Omnipod and giving it a substantial go. I‚Äôve got enough data points to share my true thoughts. I‚Äôll even give it a 1-10 rating at the end of this. Not having a tube is awesome‚Ä¶.That‚Äôs too easy though.¬† 1. So REAL #1: The site changes are FAST. I thought I was fast on Tandem, where I could get a site change done in about five minutes.¬† With these, it‚Äôs literally taking me 128 seconds (yes, I timed it). 2. The pod is not as invasive as I thought it would be. I expected this big ole thing attached to my body, it‚Äôs going to interfere with everything when I‚Äùm working out, feel funky when I‚Äôm sitting‚Ä¶and¬† I barely even notice when it‚Äôs on half the time. 3. However, the biggest pet peeve so far, the pod doesn‚Äôt always pick up when I dose. For example, I dose off the PDM, and when I was in Vegas in a crowded place, the pod wouldn‚Äôt accept my dose unless I put the PDM right next to the pod. Nothing is perfect, and this is a pretty good start. So far, I would give it a 8.5/10. I have way more thoughts on this if you would like to see an even more comprehensive review or a Part 2. #omnipod #type1diabetic #diabeteseducator #typeonediabetes #bloodsugarsupport #diabeteslife #diabetesmellitus

You can‚Äôt let your insulin overheat‚Ä¶ or you are doomed as a person with diabetes. As someone living with diabetes and a registered dietitian and certified diabetes educator myself, one of the biggest fears many people with diabetes have when traveling is the possibility of their insulin going bad.‚Ä®‚Ä®The most common way for this to happen is the insulin overheats‚Ä¶ And because insulin is a protein, ICYMI, proteins, when they get too warm, will start to unravel. So, your insulin will suddenly start to work a lot less effectively, meaning high blood sugars for you Your trip could be ruined. Whether or not I am traveling to a warm climate, I am all about taking a soft cooler bag like this one from 4AllFamily to ensure there is a zero percent likelihood of the insulin getting too hot. Ideally you are picking a bag that: ¬†üí™is TSA approved (this one is) üí™one that is soft-sided (so it fits in the bag under your seat)¬† üí™has a re-freezable gel pack so when I get to my destination I can make sure it‚Äôll be ready to go for when I eventually travel home. This completely eliminates any concern of my insulin going bad and helps reduce one factor of potential stress when traveling. ‚Ä®What do you do to keep your insulin on point? #typeonediabetes #4allfamily #insulincooler #diabeteslife #bloodsugarcontrol #insulindependent

Want to learn how to do a pushup? Here‚Äôs how to make it happen I love push-ups‚Ä¶they are pretty much my favorite exercise & are so great for building upper body and core strength.  Fun fact: At some point in high school, I had a school record for pushups & it was a pretty proud mom moment when my son told me he broke his school record for push ups this week. My husband is actually the only person who ever beat me in a pushup contest (so I tease him that that‚Äôs the reason I married him LOL) The key to an effective pushup is good form (or you won‚Äôt work the right muscles in the right way). It‚Äôs not a race to do the most, but build up slowly - with good form - so that you can do the maximum amount correctly.  This step-by-step guide will help you to build up your strength and form so that you can learn to do your first pushup or gain the strength needed to do more pushups than you could before. "A lot of the questions that I get as a type 1 diabetic are "what can you eat?" "how many carbs can you eat?" "does it hurt to poke yourself?" but I feel like I don't get asked enough... "How would you treat an emergency low blood sugar if you were to be extremely low or unconscious?" My answer is Gvoke HypoPen¬Æ (glucagon injection). The steps are simple; Pull the red cap off, push and hold the yellow end down against your skin at one of the approved injections sites and slowly count to 5.  Call for emergency medical help after Gvoke HypoPen¬Æ has been injected. Patients can even administer Gvoke HypoPen¬Æ to themselves in certain situations! For full detailed instructions on how or when to use Gvoke HypoPen¬Æ go to www.gvokeglucagon.com." It has long been thought that hormonal imbalances are genetic, based on a person‚Äôs family history and other physiological factors. üßê However, a more common cause of hormonal imbalances is actually lifestyle habits.  Factors like stress, poor nutritional habits, sedentary behavior, and sleep disruptions can all contribute to the development of hormonal imbalances by affecting various hormones in the body. üß¨ By identifying and addressing these behavioral causes, it is possible to reduce or eliminate hormonal imbalances through changes to diet and lifestyle. PERFECTION IS NOT NECESSARY. I was recently scrolling through TikTok when I happened upon a beautiful and strong looking body builder who was answering a user question: "How do you maintain this physique?" And her answer was: "I don't. It's not possible." This honesty was SO refreshing, and I have to say I could use a little bit more of it in the online diabetes community.  I, even as a long term "expert" in my diabetes and a certified specialist, can't reasonable maintain a 5.4 A1c. Did I get there at one point to see if I could? Yeah. Was it kinda miserable? Yeah.  Just as I work on with my clients, I practice balance in my own life. And that means tossing out some "ideal" numbers from time to time.
